text.b: Notice of Preparation of a Draft Environmental Impact Report

page.text: In implementing its duties under the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA), the City of Monte
Sereno, serving as Lead Agency, intends to prepare an Environmental Impact Report (EIR) for the
Monte Sereno General Plan Amendment, Zoning Code Amendment, and Prezoning (hereinafter
“proposed project”) to add a new land use designation to the General Plan Land Use Element (Multi-
Family Residential, 3 to 8 dwelling units per acre) and other related actions discussed below. In
accordance with Section 15082 of the CEQA Guidelines, the City of Monte Sereno has prepared this
Notice of Preparation (NOP) to provide responsible and trustee agencies with sufficient information
describing the proposed project and its potential environmental effects.
The City of Monte Sereno will be the Lead Agency and will prepare an Environmental Impact Report
(EIR) for the project identified below. If you are a public agency, we need to know the views of your
agency as to the scope and content of the environmental information which is germane to your agency’s
statutory responsibilities in connection with the proposed project. Your agency may need to use the EIR
prepared by our agency when considering your permit or other approval for the project. If you are a
member of the public, you are also invited to provide comments on the scope and content of the EIR.
The project description, location, and the potential environmental effects are included below.
As specified by the CEQA Guidelines, the NOP will be circulated for a 30-day review period from
Friday, October 26, 2012 to Monday November 26, 2012. Due to the time limits mandated by State
law, your response must be sent at the earliest possible date but not later than the end of the review
period (November 26, 2012). Please send or email your response to Erin Ventura, Associate City Planner
at the contact information provided above.
The City will be conducting a public scoping meeting on the proposed project on Tuesday November 13,
2012 from 7:00 to 9:00 PM at City Hall, located at

The 4.45-acre project site is located at 18840 Saratoga Los Gatos Road/State Route 9 in
the unincorporated Santa Clara County, adjacent to the City of Monte Sereno. Figure 1,
Regional Location, illustrates the regional context of the project; Figure 2, Project
Vicinity, identifies the site in relation to the City of Monte Sereno and State Route 9;
Figure 3, Project Aerial, shows approximate project site boundaries on an aerial image;
and Figure 4, Proposed Revised Figure LU-2 Land Use Designations, presents the revised
General Plan land use map identifying the addition of the new proposed land use
The proposed project is a general plan amendment, zoning code
amendment, and pre-zoning the project site. The City is proposing these
changes as part of their process to implement Housing Element Program H-
General Plan Amendment: The proposed project includes adding a new
land use designation to the General Plan Land Use Element (Multi-Family
Residential, 3 to 8 D.U./Acre), adding a text description of the new land
use, and changing the general plan land use map to include and show the
location of the new land use. Figure 4, Proposed Revised Figure LU-2,
Land Use Designations, is the proposed new general plan land use map.
Zoning Code Amendment: The proposed project includes the creation of a
new zoning district to the City of Monte Sereno Planning and Zoning Code:
RM-Multi-Family Residential District. The creation of this new zoning
district includes both text and map changes.
Pre-zoning: The proposed project includes pre-zoning the 4.45-acre project
site to the new RM-Multi-Family Residential District, which is consistent
with the proposed new land use designation. The pre-zoning would allow
for a maximum of 35 dwelling units on the project site.
Annexation: Future development of the property will require annexation by
the City of Monte Sereno. Annexation will be considered at the request of

The purpose of this document is to provide a timeline and brief summary of the background
relating to annexation of unincorporated pockets, the development of the City’s General Plan and
the implementation of Housing Element Program 3.10. This program requires that by the end of
July 2011 the City study whether or not to zone for multifamily and begin annexation of an 11
acre portion of the County unincorporated pocket (study area). The City is not compelled to
rezone or to annex the study area. However, if the City Council determines that a change in
zoning and annexation is not appropriate for the study area, then the Housing Element Program
3.10 requires the City to look at other locations within the City to provide for multifamily
opportunities by the end of December 2012.
June 1, 2010. The City Council conducted public hearings and approved the Environmental
Determination for the Housing Element revision, and adopted the proposed Housing
June 8, 2010. The City staff transmits the adopted Housing Element to the State Department of
Housing and Community Development for their review and certification.
August 3, 2010. At this City Council meeting the City Council considered the implementation
September 7, 2010. The State Department of Housing and Community Development transmits a
letter to the City to certify the City’s adopted Housing Element is compliant with State law.
September 30, 2010. The City Council conducted a public workshop to inform the public and
receive testimony about the housing requirements of the State and the City’s Housing
Element program 3.10. Staff presented information on what the City has done to this point
regarding the Housing Element implementation and what the next steps are in the process.
March 15, 2011. The City conducted a public workshop to receive public input on the various
alternatives to comply with the City Housing Element program 3.10. Specifically,
Alternative 1-is to continue to evaluate the 11 acres of County unincorporated land for
multifamily zoning. Alternative 2-is to examine other areas of the City to provide for
multifamily opportunities. Alternative 3-is to revise the City Housing Element and negotiate
certification with the State. There was no action taken by the Council on the alternatives.
At this meeting the City Council also accepted the Annual Housing Element Progress report
April 5, 2011. At this City Council meeting the Council received public comment on the next
steps in the process. The Council determined to conduct another study session on the issue
and set the date for May 3, 2011.
May 3, 2011. The City Council conducted a study session on Housing Element program 3.10.
After public input the Council discussed the various alternatives. Alternative 1-is to continue
to evaluate the 11 acres of County unincorporated land for multifamily zoning. Alternative
2-is to examine other areas of the City to provide for multifamily opportunities. Alternative
3-is to revise the City Housing Element and negotiate certification with the State. The
Council directed staff to pursue Alternative #2, with a 4-1 vote.
June 21, 2011. The City Council discussed the process for identifying future alternatives for the
implementation of Housing Element program 3.10. Following public input there was
Council consensus to direct staff to bring a draft of the criteria to be used for identifying and
considering alternative locations to the August 2nd Council meeting.
August 2, 2011. The City Council discussed the criteria to be used for possible site
consideration. Although there was consensus on the criteria as revised by the Council, the
Council did not formally adopt the criteria.
November 15, 2011. The City Council conducted a special meeting. The meeting was held at
the local elementary school multi purpose room to accommodate the anticipated large
audience as the City mailed public notices to all residents in the City and County pockets of
the meeting. At this meeting the Council considered the various site alternatives developed
by staff for potential multi-family use consideration. The potential sites were developed by
staff using the site selection criteria discussed previously by the City Council. There were
essentially, five distinct areas proposed by City Staff, including the property located at 18840
Saratoga Los Gatos Road (La Hacienda). By a 4-1 vote the Council directed staff to proceed
in evaluating the La hacienda site for potential multi-family uses.
